<HEADLINE>
FT  04 OCT 93 / A crowd with only one aim: armed rebellion - John Lloyd
witnesses the turmoil on the capital's streets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CROWD, gathering in October Square under the capital's largest Lenin
statue, wasted no time on speeches.
With tough young men, many in camouflage, in the vanguard the crowd launched
itself on the police line across the Moscow River bridge just past Gorky
Park.
It was a march which by nightfall would take many of them into a pitched
battle with forces loyal to President Boris Yeltsin in a fight for control
of Moscow.
The speed of their advance along the ring road left police and interior
ministry trucks and buses abandoned: these were smashed, their contents
looted. From one, bizarrely, came a big carton of Wagon Wheel biscuits,
which were grabbed hungrily. 'See what the democrats give to their
defenders', screamed one woman.' I can't buy these for my kids'.
At Smolenskaya Square, in front of the Foreign Ministry, the police again
tried to hold them with smoke bombs and water cannon: again they were swept
aside.
Between the Foreign Ministry and the US Embassy, also on the ring road, a
bus full of troops was surrounded by men and women hurling rocks through the
windows as the troops huddled behind their shields. A few leaders tried to
tear away their enraged comrades, shouting: 'Don't waste your time, get to
the White House'.
Through the perfect autumn afternoon the crowd swept on towards the
parliament building. As they surged up to the barricades blocking the
entrance to the White House, automatic fire rang out. Most dived to the
street or cowered behind trees and lamp posts. The firing, however, seemed
mainly into the air - though it was then, probably, that a policeman was
shot dead and another injured. Again the troops fell back and scattered.
The crowd broke through and charged up the ramp and round to the back of the
parliament, where they were embraced by the long-term defenders. On the
balcony stood a cheering group of deputies and staff.
Then, to a huge cheer, out came General Alexander Rutskoi, his bodyguards
holding a flak jacket before him as he gripped the microphone. His suit
freshly-pressed, he addressed the crowd.
'All able men who wish to join us, form yourself into detachments before the
White House. You'll be given arms: we'll take the mayor's office and then
Ostankino (the TV centre, some 4-5 kms away)'.
Some 30 to 40 armed defenders then attacked the mayor's office. A captured
truck was reversed against the barred glass door, smashing it back into the
foyer. The firing stopped. Minutes later troops sheltering in the building
smashed through a window to one side and trotted away across the street as
White House defenders contemptuously fired into the air above them.
The crowd invaded the mayor's office, taking hostages almost at once. Their
captives were spat on and beaten.
Behind the building, some dejected soldiers led by a corporal named
Alaxander were also held captive. Asked if he would now join the
parliamentary side, he said: 'I don't want to fight against the people . . .
I can't answer that.' A doctor standing by said three people had been
injured seriously.
Many of the White House defenders wore flashes with 'Russian National Unity'
on them; others wore a swastika-like device. Mr Ilya Konstantinnov, one of
the hardest-line deputies and a leader of the Russian Unity political bloc,
appeared to be in command of the operation. 'Now,' he called to the men,
'forward to Ostankino'.
The crowd, many waving sub machine guns, baying with victory, swept back up
the New Arbat - to meet a second crowd of thousands of demonstrators coming
along the inner ring from the direction of the Foreign Ministry.
The crowd, which had begun the day at 5,000 - 10,000 strong had now grown to
30,000 - 40,000. All were intent on going to Ostankino, hated for its
unequivocal support over the past two weeks for President Boris Yeltsin.
Round the ring road they went, the banners out now - mostly the Soviet red
flag and a few portraits of Stalin. As they passed the newly refurbished US
embassy, they chanted, in Russian and English - 'Yankee Go Home' or
'Sovyetsky Soyuz' (Soviet Union).
Ostankino appeared lightly guarded. It was already dark when the frontal
assault began, with heavy explosions punctuating the machine gun fire. From
within the building, fire was returned.
Behind the front line, youths smashed fences to form barricades and build
fires. 'What the devil do you think your hands are for?' one demanded. 'Help
us]'
By 11pm the firing had grown heavier and more frequent. Bullets raced down
the avenue leading to the centre, forcing people to their bellies. Fires had
broken out on the first floor and the deployment of the armoured personnel
carriers seemed to have halted the advance of the parliamentary forces.
</TEXT>
