<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 93 / Khmer Rouge leader pays homage to king
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAIN SIMPSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PHNOM PENH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Khieu Samphan, president of the radical Khmer Rouge in Cambodia,
yesterday arrived in the capital, Phnom Penh, for talks with King Norodom
Sihanouk, writes Iain Simpson in Phnom Penh.
The Khmer Rouge is at its lowest ebb for almost three decades, having
suffered several military setbacks in the past six weeks.
On his arrival, Mr Khieu said he had come to 'pay our respectful homage' to
King Sihanouk, and to show Khmer Rouge support for the monarchy and for the
new Cambodian constitution. However, he avoided mentioning the new
government, which the group has repeatedly attacked via its clandestine
radio station.
The day before his arrival in the city, the two Cambodian prime ministers
wrote to Mr Khieu, laying out the conditions for their holding peace talks
with the Khmer Rouge. These included its recognition of what they called the
'royal and legitimate government', and its acceptance that the talks would
be between a legal government and a group, not between two equal entities.
The Khmer Rouge responded with its own proposal of a ceasefire monitored by
an independent commission.
</TEXT>
