<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 93 / Peru rebel chief 'seeks peace deal'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SALLY BOWEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LIMA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Abimael Guzman, the jailed leader of the Maoist guerrilla group Shining
Path (Sendero Luminoso), is offering to negotiate a peace accord with the
Peruvian government, President Alberto Fujimori told the UN general assembly
in New York yesterday.
At a news conference after his address, Mr Fujimori showed reporters a
hand-written letter which seemed to bear the signatures of Mr Guzman and his
chief lieutenant, Ms Elena Iparraguirre, verified by their fingerprints.
Seeming to abandon a long-maintained rejection of any political line but his
own, Mr Guzman recognises Mr Fujimori as president and requests
'conversations which would lead to the conclusion of the war'. Thirteen
years of conflict have cost 26,000 Peruvian lives and the equivalent of some
Dollars 22bn (Pounds 14bn) in damage.
The letter was written from the prison at the naval base at Callao, the port
of Lima, where Mr Guzman and three other senior Shining Path people are
serving life sentences.
Mr Fujimori rejected any prospect of negotiating reductions in the leaders'
sentences.
</TEXT>
