<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / International Company News: Martin Marietta unveils Dollars
1.5bn cost-cutting plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MARTIN Marietta, the US defence contractor, yesterday announced a
consolidation plan intended to reduce operating costs by Dollars 1.5bn over
the next five years.
The restructuring, which involves the closure of facilities in seven states
and a further 2,000 job losses, follows Marietta's Dollars 3.05bn
acquisition of General Electric's aerospace division earlier this year.
The merger created the world's largest aerospace electronics group, with
annual revenues of about Dollars 11bn. The group's main products include
space equipment, missiles, satellites, avionics and communications systems.
Before the deal was approved in April, Mr Norman Augustine, Marietta's
chairman, warned that significant cuts would be necessary to eliminate
overcapacity and duplication in administration, research and production.
Most of the facilities to be shut or relocated under the plan were formerly
operated by GE. The former GE aerospace headquarters in Valley Forge,
Pennsylvania, will consolidate with Martin Marietta's main office in
Bethesda, Maryland, with a 40 per cent cut in staff.
GE's former Automated Systems arm, which produces simulation and test
systems for the military at facilities in Florida and Massachusetts, will
merge with Marietta's Electronic Systems Center in Orlando, Florida.
In addition to cutting costs, Marietta said the consolidation was intended
to 'put together complementary technologies under one group'. The resulting
'synergies', the company said, would lead to greater market penetration and
higher shares.
The redundancies announced yesterday are in addition to 9,000 jobs the
company previously said it would eliminate this year. The figure brings the
total number of positions that Marietta and GE Aerospace have cut since 1987
to 46,000. The down-sizing reflects sharp reductions in defence spending, as
well as efforts to improve productivity.
The scope of the consolidation was in line with analysts' expectations. At
the close of trading on Wall Street, Marietta shares were up Dollars  3/8 at
Dollars 89.
</TEXT>
