<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / International Company News: Murdoch agrees to resume role at
NY Post
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Rupert Murdoch has agreed to resume publishing the New York Post
following a decision by leaders of the newspaper's production unions to
break a four-day strike by journalists. However, it was not clear last night
if the paper would be on news-stands this morning.
Earlier this week, Mr Murdoch said he was walking away from his agreement to
manage the bankrupt tabloid after members of the Newspaper Guild,
representing journalists and advertising staff, walked out, and drivers and
printers refused to cross the guild's picket line.
The guild is fighting Mr Murdoch's demands to slash severance pay and to
have the right to dismiss any employee, regardless of seniority, within a
four-month period.
However after leaders of the paper's eight craft unions, including printers
and drivers, said on Wednesday their members would return to work, Mr
Murdoch extended his management contract by one week. He is expected to
complete his Dollars 25m purchase of the paper within a week, assuming no
further stoppages.
The support of the journalists by other union members was a surprise. Mr
Murdoch had struck agreements with all of The Post's other unions in July.
At the time, guild members agreed to return to work while negotiations
continued.
Mr Colin Miner, a reporter at The Post said: 'It was a miracle that the
drivers didn't cross on Monday. It's unlikely to happen again.'
</TEXT>
