<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / International Company News: Sumitomo to write off losses at
finance unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SUMITOMO Corporation, the Japanese trading house, is to write off
unspecified securities losses incurred by a financial subsidiary which had
invested Y80bn (Dollars 741m) through special trading accounts to supplement
core profits.
Many Japanese companies, including trading houses, had come to regard stock
investment as a 'new profit centre' during the late 1980s, but have since
suffered bruising losses, most often on tokkin, or specified money trusts.
Tokkin became popular during the 1980s, as capital gains could be converted
to income, prompting some companies to use the trusts for investment in
risky stocks.
However, the fall of Tokyo stock prices in 1990 meant that investors
suffered large losses.
Sumitomo said the subsidiary, SC Finance, had appraisal losses of about
Y20bn at the end of March, when the Nikkei index closed at 18,591, far below
the market peak of 38,915.87 of late December 1989.
The index closed at 20,105.71 yesterday.
The move by Sumitomo follows Mitsubishi Corporation's rescue earlier this
year of a subsidiary, MC Finance, which had accumulated losses of Y28bn on
securities investments of about Y70bn.
Mitsubishi established MC Finance to act as a banker for subsidiaries,
borrowing large sums from banks at discount rates and passing on the savings
to smaller members of the group. The company was later encouraged to
generate income through stock investment.
Sumitomo did not say what impact the write-off would have on pre-tax profit
for the first half, which ended yesterday, but the company is expected to
sell other stocks to cover the losses incurred.
In the year ended in March, Sumitomo reported an appraisal loss on
securities holdings of Y18.7bn and had a special profit of Y12.9bn on a
property sale.
</TEXT>
