<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / UK Company News: Sherwood Group shows 5% fall to Pounds
7.76m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHERWOOD GROUP, the socks and lace manufacturer, yesterday reported its
first decline in interim profits since its flotation in 1986.
Pre-tax profits fell 5 per cent to Pounds 7.76m (Pounds 8.18m) for the first
six months of 1993.
Mr David Parker, chairman, blamed recession in continental Europe for
depressing profit margins on lace sales. Operating profit in lace fell from
Pounds 5.59m to Pounds 4.64m, while turnover rose from Pounds 37m to Pounds
39.9m.
The company is increasingly dependent on overseas sales: 48 per cent of
total turnover of Pounds 69.7m (Pounds 66m) now takes place outside the UK.
Nevertheless the interim dividend goes up to 1p (0.9p), a measure of 'the
board's confidence in the future', said Mr Parker.
Earnings per share fell from 5.3p to 4.8p, partly reflecting the issue of
shares for the Pounds 19.6m acquisition in May of Lepel, the Italian
lingerie maker.
Mr Parker said that the acquisition would be earnings enhancing over the
full year. Garment sales tend to be substantially higher in the second half
and the acquisition would further add to the skewing of sales and profits
towards the second half.
Analysts said that pre-tax profits for the full year should be about Pounds
21m, beating 1992's Pounds 16.9m.
'Wherever we can cut costs, we will,' said Mr Parker. 'But margins will
remain under pressure in the second half too.'
Some 300 jobs had been cut this year, although another 210 people were taken
on with Lepel.
The company is also concentrating on higher margin products. It is reducing
production of curtain lace to concentrate on clothing lace using Textronic
machines which create a three dimensional fabric.
Investment is falling from an 'exceptionally high figure last year' of
Pounds 11.6m to Pounds 9.5m for the full year.
</TEXT>
