<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / Forte disappoints with Pounds 37m halfway
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORTE, the hotels and restaurants group, yesterday announced interim pre-tax
profits at the bottom end of expectations and said conditions remained
depressed in both the UK and continental Europe.
Pre-tax profits of Pounds 37m for the six months to July 31 compared with a
restated Pounds 19m. But most analysts had been looking for recovery in its
hotels business to show through more strongly.
Forte also disappointed some in the City who had been hoping for an
announcement on the sale of the Harvester restaurant chain.
The share price fell 10p to 227p.
Sales were down to Pounds 1.1bn from Pounds 1.36bn. The previous figure,
however, included Pounds 416m from the Gardner Merchant contract catering
business, sold at the end of 1992.
London hotels provided one bright spot, with sales up 9 per cent and profits
up 28 per cent. Visitor numbers from mainland Europe fell, but Mr Rocco
Forte, chairman, said there had been a 20 per cent increase in US visitors.
Provincial UK hotels raised profits on static sales as a result of cost
savings. Continental European hotels deteriorated, however, as recession
took hold.
In the US, the Travelodge chain saw occupancy rise by 2 per cent and room
rates by 3 per cent. This was offset by a poor performance from luxury
hotels in New York.
Worldwide hotel profits were up 8 per cent to Pounds 43m on sales up 7 per
cent to Pounds 456m.
The Relais autoroute restaurant chain in France, acquired last December, was
another strong performer. Forte said sales had increased 6 per cent, despite
the impact of recession. Mr Forte said the group had improved Relais'
performance by adding sales points during peak summer periods.
In the UK, higher profits from the Welcome Break, Happy Eater and Little
Chef roadside chains came despite a 4 per cent fall in total UK motor
traffic in the first quarter of 1993 and a 3 per cent fall in the second
quarter. This was offset by the poor performance of city centre restaurants.
With net debt at Pounds 1.3bn, Forte's gearing rose to 50 per cent compared
with 44 per cent a year ago. Borrowings have been restructured, however, so
that 48 per cent is now repayable within five years, compared with 83 per
cent last January.
The interim dividend was maintained at 2.75p, just covered by earnings per
share of 2.8p, compared with 1p.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
