<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 93 / Du Pont cuts 860 UK jobs as global rethink on nylon starts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DU PONT, the world's biggest nylon supplier, is to shut a factory in
Pontypool, South Wales, and cut production at three other sites with the
loss of 860 jobs.
The job cuts, more than 17 per cent of the company's UK workforce in nylon,
are at plants Du Pont bought from Imperial Chemical Industries in July.
Further losses could follow early next year after an in-house analysis of Du
Pont's world nylon activities.
Mr Alan Titus, managing director of Du Pont Nylon Europe, blamed
overcapacity in world markets, duplication of production with US and German
plants, and a drift from nylon to other synthetic fibres for clothing and
carpet textiles.
Pontypool will lose 400 jobs when a nylon textile filament plant and
associated site services shut at the end of the year. Another plant in
Pontypool, which makes the Dacron nylon brand, will stay open.
A further 250 jobs will be lost in Brockworth, Gloucestershire, which has a
technical centre that is 'too big for the size and quality of the European
nylon business', said Mr Titus.
Some 150 jobs will be lost at Doncaster, South Yorkshire, as Du Pont ends
production of carpet staple fibre - the short sections of nylon filament
that are later spun into yarn. The final 60 jobs are to go at Wilton,
Cleveland, as part of a general cost-cutting programme.
Du Pont said it would be looking for voluntary redundancies and redeployment
but that 'involuntary separations will probably be required at some sites'.
Mr Titus warned of possible further job cuts. 'This first phase is doing
things that appear obvious to us,' said Mr Titus. 'It does not represent a
position of sustained financial health.'
Last week, Du Pont's global nylon business began 'a fundamental analysis of
our entire operations to develop further plans to get us back on the path to
sustained profitability.'
The UK nylon plants have already borne a series of job reduction programmes.
When talks on the deal with ICI began in April 1992, there were 6,100 on the
payroll in Europe, the number falling to 5,200 when ICI handed over control.
Another 220 job losses in Oestringen, south of Frankfurt, Germany, were also
announced yesterday, as well as a further 80 spread throughout European
plants.
The cuts follow 1,600 job cuts two weeks ago in Du Pont north American nylon
production sites. At the time, Du Pont's US management warned that there
would be job cuts in Europe.
</TEXT>
